  "prompt": "How do I reverse the words in a String without reversing each character and not using builtin functions like split and substring in C#?",
  "response": "Here's a solution to reverse the words in a string without using built-in split or substring functions in C#:\n\n```csharp\npublic static string ReverseWords(string input)\n{\n    // Handle null or empty string\n    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(input))\n        return input;\n\n    // Trim leading and trailing spaces\n    input = input.Trim();\n\n    // Initialize result string and temporary word builder\n    string result = \"\";\n    string currentWord = \"\";\n\n    // Iterate through the string from right to left\n    for (int i = input.Length - 1; i >= 0; i--)\n    {\n        // If current character is not a space, add to current word\n        if (input[i] != ' ')\n        {\n            currentWord = input[i] + currentWord;\n        }\n        \n        // When we encounter a space or reach the start of the string\n        if (input[i] == ' ' || i == 0)\n        {\n            // Add the current word to result if it's not empty\n            if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(currentWord))\n            {\n                // Add space before the word if result is not empty\n                if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(result))\n                    result += \" \";\n                \n                result += currentWord;\n                currentWord = \"\";\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    return result;\n}\n\n// Example usage\nstatic void Main(string[] args)\n{\n    string input = \"Hello World Coding\";\n    string reversed = ReverseWords(input);\n    Console.WriteLine(reversed); // Output: \"Coding World Hello\"\n}\n```\n\nThis solution has several key characteristics:\n\n1. It works without using `Split()` or `Substring()`.\n2. It handles multiple spaces between words.\n3. It trims leading and trailing spaces.\n4. It preserves the original word order when reversed.\n\nAlternative approach using character array manipulation:\n\n```csharp\npublic static string ReverseWords(string input)\n{\n    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(input))\n        return input;\n\n    // Convert string to char array\n    char[] chars = input.ToCharArray();\n    \n    // Reverse the entire string\n    ReverseCharArray(chars, 0, chars.Length - 1);\n\n    // Reverse individual words\n    int start = 0;\n    for (int end = 0; end < chars.Length; end++)\n    {\n        if (chars[end] == ' ')\n        {\n            ReverseCharArray(chars, start, end - 1);\n            start = end + 1;\n        }\n    }\n\n    // Reverse the last word\n    ReverseCharArray(chars, start, chars.Length - 1);\n\n    return new string(chars);\n}\n\n// Helper method to reverse a portion of char array\nprivate static void ReverseCharArray(char[] chars, int start, int end)\n{\n    while (start < end)\n    {\n        char temp = chars[start];\n        chars[start] = chars[end];\n        chars[end] = temp;\n        start++;\n        end--;\n    }\n}\n\n// Example usage\nstatic void Main(string[] args)\n{\n    string input = \"Hello World Coding\";\n    string reversed = ReverseWords(input);\n    Console.WriteLine(reversed); // Output: \"Coding World Hello\"\n}\n```\n\nThis alternative approach:\n1. First reverses the entire string\n2. Then reverses each individual word\n3. Works in-place with O(1) extra space\n4. Has a time complexity of O(n)\n\nBoth solutions avoid using built-in split or substring methods and effectively reverse the words in a string.\n\nChoose the approach that best fits your specific requirements and coding style. The first solution is more straightforward and easier to understand, while the second solution is more space-efficient.",
